        content: 'Housing intact male animals together is one of the most dangerous situations in livestock management. Rams (male sheep) and bucks (male goats) are both aggressive during breeding season, and keeping them together requires careful management to prevent serious injuries or death.\n\nRams are generally more dangerous than bucks because of their fighting style. Rams back up and charge head-on at full speed, delivering devastating impacts that can break bones, cause internal injuries, and kill other animals.\n\nA charging ram can also seriously injure or kill a human. Bucks fight differently, rearing up and clashing horns from above, which is less forceful than a ram\'s charge but still dangerous.\n\nIf you need to keep rams and bucks in the same area, provide ample space so they can establish territories without constant confrontation. Remove them to separate areas during breeding season when hormones and aggression peak.\n\nNever turn a ram into a pen with goats during rut, as the ram may attack the goats with potentially lethal force. Wether goats (castrated males) are generally much calmer than intact bucks, but they can still display aggressive behaviors, especially if they were wethered late.\n\nA wether that was intact for a year or more may retain some buck-like behaviors including head-butting, mounting, and territorial aggression. Early wethering (8-12 weeks) produces the calmest, most manageable male goats.\n\nWethers make excellent pets, pack goats, and companions for does between breeding seasons.',
