        heading: 'Goat Bites, Riding Goats, and Physical Safety Around Goats',
        content: 'Goats are generally gentle animals, but they can bite, and there are physical activities involving goats that people attempt that are genuinely unsafe. Understanding goat behavior and physical limitations keeps both you and your goats safe.\n\nGoats do bite, but it is rarely aggressive. Goats explore the world with their mouths, much like puppies, and most "bites" are actually investigative nibbles.\n\nThey will mouth your clothes, fingers, hair, and anything else within reach. These nibbles are usually painless or mildly uncomfortable.\n\nTrue aggressive bites from bucks or frightened goats can be more forceful and may break skin, but this is uncommon with well-socialized animals. Goats have a dental pad on top and teeth on the bottom of their front mouth (no upper front teeth), which means their bite is more of a pinch than a puncture.\n\nTheir back molars, however, are strong enough to grind tough browse, so a bite on the finger from back teeth can be painful. Teach children to keep fingers flat when hand-feeding goats, just as you would with horses.\n\nRiding goats is a topic that comes up surprisingly often, usually from parents wondering if their children can ride the family goats. The short answer is no.\n\nEven large breed goats like Boers cannot safely carry the weight of a person on their backs. Goat spines are not designed for bearing weight from above the way horse spines are.\n\nAttempting to ride a goat risks spinal injuries, broken legs, and permanent damage to the animal. Small children sometimes sit briefly on large, calm goats for photos, but this should be momentary and supervised, never an actual riding activity.\n\nGoat screaming is another behavior that alarms new owners but is usually harmless. Goats are vocal animals and some breeds (Nubians are notorious) are louder than others.\n\nGoats scream when hungry, lonely, in heat, or simply demanding attention. While the sound can be startling and sometimes eerily human-like, it is normal goat communication.',
